    "summary": "The Vinča culture was a Neolithic and Chalcolithic culture centered on the middle Danube region, flourishing in present-day Serbia, Romania, Bulgaria, and Hungary between approximately 5500 and 4500 BCE. Named after the eponymous site near Belgrade, the Vinča culture is notable for its large, densely populated settlements — some covering over 30 hectares — and for producing the [[event:1522|Vinča symbolic script]], one of the earliest known systems of graphical notation in the world.\n\nVinča communities were agricultural, cultivating wheat, barley, and peas and herding cattle, sheep, and pigs. Their settlements were among the largest in Neolithic Europe, with populations estimated in the hundreds to low thousands. Houses were rectangular, built from timber and clay, and arranged along streets in a planned manner, demonstrating a high degree of social organization. Vinča material culture is characterized by distinctive dark burnished pottery and an extensive tradition of clay figurines representing stylized human and animal forms.\n\nThe Vinča culture participated in Copper Age metallurgy at an early date, connected to the broader Chalcolithic florescence of southeastern Europe that included the [[event:1567|earliest copper mining]] in the Balkans. Its dense, organized settlements and rich material culture make it one of the most significant Neolithic cultures in European prehistory, influencing later Balkan cultures and contributing to the development of metal-age societies in the region.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vin%C4%8Da_culture",
